\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 When were you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 1930.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And the year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 1894.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 At seventy Oxford Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And you lived in one house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Until I was six - about six, somewhere about six years old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 We moved to - down here Tidmarsh Street, at 24.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And you've lived here ever since?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes. Barring when I was in the Army of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Do you remember why the family made these moves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes. Yes, because the family enlarged and we only had two bedrooms there and this one had three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 You had brothers and sisters older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes. I had - two elder brothers and one elder sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And then the younger ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Younger, that's - two - two sisters - I had three sisters one - passed away. Three sisters and one brother younger than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And how much was there between them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh I know - there was not really a year - not - not - a little over two years or something like that. Somewhere about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Well I couldn't - I couldn't tell you, I - maybe about - 
I mean, it's a thing we - I think it's a thing we never discussed sort of thing you see. They wouldn't - perhaps it wouldn't be allowed - we weren't allowed to ask.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Where did he come from then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Reading he came, yes. But - I am - I did hear that 
he came from - the area and I also heard that he came from Croydon. Whether is was - whether it was or - whether that was true or not I don't know, but of course I knew him - me father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And he was a professional soldier?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes, a professional soldier. In the - the Royal Bucks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 He was - just labouring you see, then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did he have any casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Well they was - nearly all part time jobs, well he got a job for a little while - for a lot of years then 
it was - it - you were lucky if you had a job at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Too many times. Too many times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Tell me about him going to Wales?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes, he went - I remember that when he marched - went with a d
ozen of them went down to Wales and when he came back he told us he was better - rightly or wrongly, he met by his - people at the village - the Marney village with the pickstaffs like - pickaxe staves and - back he had to come you see because - work was 
the same there, although they had a bit more - more slack there than they did here. Anyway - well I was - oh they went back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 You don't know how old your mother was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No. There wasn't much difference between - father's and mother's ages.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 She was Reading. As far as I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Had she have any jobs before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Well all - all I could say is that she was in like the - nursing profession, because I couldn't tell you about that at all. Oh y
es, it was one of those things in those days, I mean, like children you mustn't discuss your parents' doings. Unless you wanted a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did she work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes. She went out working like as - seeing the people who were - passing away
 and then laid 'em out or - births she went, anything like that, yes. Never know when there was going to be a knock on the door for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 You don't know how many hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Hours she put in? Oh - of course they was restricted to herself, I mean, if 
she put in too many for her she used to put the names in she was with them. She would - she - she would stop on - she - if she was needed she stopped there if - for nothing. For nothing. Like oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  you do this or not, she used to do that for nothing when she went to peoples who was ill. She was good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Who looked after the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Mother - my mother's mother, our granny. Oh she was good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 There were three bedrooms in the house in Oxford Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No, two - two bedrooms in Oxford Road. And here - three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 How many living rooms were there there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Only two. Two up there, two living rooms and - a bit of a scullery. Were we've got this one - about - what we always call it, the front room, the middle kitchen, back kitchen and a little scullery. See? Well upstairs we've got three bedrooms and a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 box room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
, see, we've got no bathroom. But we could have it converted to a bathroom, but as we are now we can't afford it. Because we'd have to pay - we're - we're a tenant see? And that's our landlord over there, he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 won\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 do a thing for us. And if he had it - if he did have it with the council help he - we should have to pay about ten or eleven shillings more a week rent, which we cannot afford, I mean, that's paying ten shillings for a bath I 
tell my wife, so it is. See, well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 What about your grandmother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh granny, yes, oh yes, well of course granny would. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. She'd have liked to have been able to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Was the washing done at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes. Yes, all washing was done at home, in the old fashioned copper what they used to have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did your mother or father }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 mend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  or make the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Well some of them of course, making - 'course that's where my mother was a sort of a bit lucky you know, when she was out - she would get some clothes given her you know by out of fashion and outfit a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Were the clothes new or secondhand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Oh secondhand. We - I don't know when I had a new - anything new. That's as true as I'm sitting here, I can't remember having a new suit. I had - most probably - remember a coat made out of my father's old red tunic - for the Ar
my, I remember going - wearing that - they had red tunics them days when they weren't fighting - when they was - was too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Where did they usually buy secondhand clothes, in the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Probably. Yes, there was - the - the cheapest was on - used to 
be in Union Street right in the centre of the town. It's still there now, Union Street is, in the centre of town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did you ever have new shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Well we did have them occasionally but - it was like - as I say, me - had brothers and - handed it dow
n sort of fashion. I tell you I went to school once with me father's and had a good hiding for a going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. He was - he was never - that way. At times - at times - now my father
 is - is a very funny thing - at times, my father - like what they - what they used to call in them days on the tap, that was sober, never drank. He'd go for six months and wouldn't - say that six months wouldn't touch it. He'd go along to Pilgrim}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 s Baptis
t church along there for a Pleasant Sunday Afternoon, they often have P.S.A. for hour. And he'd have the prize, win a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 prize}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 for - being - you know, best attendance or get new members. And then all of a sudden - bake he would go, straight off - you could never last - he could never last. It - pension day it was, pension - this pension. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 Yes, he - he - they really - well I remember - we - he belonged to these }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16731435\charrsid9580092 Good Templers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 . }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 I never - I never touched a drop or hard water not until I was in the Army. Or invariably if ever I got going it would never affect me like that, I doubt it, it never have. No, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 He didn't dress or undress you or bath you or read to you or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did he take you out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. We've gone - the only - 
the only time I can - I can - he never took us out then, the only time I can remember going out with my father was when we was - was three of us was in the Army together and we was all home together, that's - that's not taking us out as children is it. An
d
 then when - when we were home he was as proud as a peacock, he'd say - I - my three sons. Of course my brother eldest next to me he would say, shut up you, to him. He - he was the same as my father like. Shut up you, that. There was some little argument 
-
 oh, my three sons. Like he was - he was proud that we was all in the Army. And the only time I see him cry, my father, was when he - he went up to join the - first world war and they wouldn't have him, too old and of course his other brother. And when my
 sister - little sister died. That's the only time I see him cry. Yes I could cry a baby, I'm - wet mop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did you have any tasks you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father, in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Not - not - it wasn't a regular t
ask with our parents you see, it wasn't - we wasn't hold to it, I mean, bar - now if my father, if he come up the road, I was up the road and I had dirty shoes and I was with my pals like you know, he'd look, slap across the face, home, clean all the kniv
es and forks - in them days there were no stainless steel, you had to clean them all with brick dust and clean every shoe and that and boot that was in house for being up there with dirty - or with hands in your pockets, he wouldn't let you stand - if he 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 caught}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 with hands in your pockets, bang you'd have it, home. All the knives, forks and spoons with this brick dust. And he'd see whether it was clean when he came home. He would see it was clean. And if }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 you\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  dirty shoes you had to do - clean all the shoes there was in the house. Because you used to get a tin of blacking then - oh a big one for a penny.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 You didn't have regular jobs you had to do to help out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Those just - he - we was all the 
same, we never had our regular jobs, no. And I can't remember in my - my elder brother - that doing any jobs or me sister. Like that sort of thing - well all they done was - I know they - I always remember them - they got the golf links like caddying. You
 
see the golf links used to be up the top, now we've got all that land with houses on now and - I never know what they done with their money, whether they give it to mother or - or how they - spent that. But I know with my second brother, Willie, it'd be i
n his pocket, the second one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 After you left school did you do anything at all, did you have to do anything in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh - no you wasn't made to do it like after I left school, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did the older children help the younger with things they found difficult like dressing or eating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh, no - we - we used to do it - we were doing all right because - I mean, my mother was so }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 nice.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  She - she'd make - she'd do anything for us, she'd starve herself for you. So's you'd have something. She was -
 she was - she thought - my mother was always worried about was the paying the rent of the house and father out of work and on the booze all night and paying the rent. She rely on him so as when he got the top - I remember when I were only a child. Go up 
to the Post Office for your dad. Go up the Post Office and tell him to come home. 'Cos she - the landlord up there, I daresay - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 their}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  name was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 Perris}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 Dunlop
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  - he was - pretty good. As - let mother go over a long - a long way without - without paying t
he rent, see, hoping that my father would pay it on pension day. See, have - well his pension was only five shillings a week and he had that on the slate that was five shillings a week. See. Well if father went into a - public house, go home, all you got 
was tears. No pay, you see, you always got his - but he never turned us out. I've seen people like all over the roads when you've read your home stuck in the street, turned out through not paying the rent but - we had a good - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 Perris}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  was a good man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 I suppose it was knowing that your mother was a good woman.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Well, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time during your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh yes, had to - to - and there were - I had to go to bed when - well when they said b
ed it was bed. You see, whenever he said bed it was bed, well there was nothing to sit up for in those days. And you wasn't allowed go grumble about your food. I said, I - I've told her, one night I said - I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 wasn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  in - and it was only sort of bread and jam you know, I said, is this bread dry? My father was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 sat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 right over there and I was sat here. What did you say? I looked at him. What did you say, he said. Of course I had to tell him. Up - up, he said, bed and bang, bang, bang, a good hiding for it and al
l. Oh mustn't say - grumble about your food, whether it was dry or not you had to eat it. Bang, bang, bang, we had it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. We all went to bed our - well maybe when we was small I expect she did but as long as I can remember went up on our own. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did you share the bedroom or bed with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Yes, brothers, well we - well now - when our little girl died there was two of us in bed with her then, she lay - as a matter of fact when she was s
till dead like, when mother come to - that's why I said I could remember him leaning over the mantelshelf in the bedroom crying in his handkerchief. 'Course she - died of measles. I remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 How many bedrooms did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Three. Three bedrooms. Me mother - of course me father and mother in the front bedroom, yes. Then the others - well, see -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And grandma?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 Yes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 ? Granny. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 
Gran used to - me sister used - had a sister - would be me sister she's older then me - she slept in the box room - with a single cot - bedstead they called them, she slept - she slept in there, I remember that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 That's how it went. And then of course the second - the second eldest brother, he joined the Army. He went in the Army he did, he went in the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 What room did you have to bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Downstairs. Didn't have a bathroom - in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 How often?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh we bath every week, have a bath every week, of a Saturday night it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 On - with you
r bath. After your bath. What clothes they were, they were always clean. Granny and mother see they get - got a bit of clean stuff about you see but it was a - the hot tub part you made a lot of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 In the middle kitchen. In that other room, that's a nice - not a bad sized room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Would you ever eat in any other room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No, we always ate in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Well - in them days we had the old - they had the fire with the o
ven on the side, like the old kitchen hearth and all. Kitchen range, that's what they call them, yes. Kitchen range. We had that - we had a kitchen range there and we had a kitchen range in the back kitchen and all. Two - and a copper for boiling was in t
he scullery you see outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 What time did you have breakfast in those days, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Yes. Well I - as I said - I - when I was old enough I had to come up here - I was up - at Bristow's the milkman at half past five in the morning. Spare
 set away. But what it was, if I was late I had to get them customers for quicker and quicker and quicker and get back and have a snack them. He fed - he fed me well, like a good man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 How many of the family had breakfast together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh nearly all them see, nearly all of us had our breakfast - it - it was generally the old - bread and jam fashion. That's all you'd get.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And you had your meal out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes. But - before that - before I was old enough to do that, we had to join the - the various 
public baths them. Used to have to go along - I used to go along to the old - wash hand basin, you know the wash hand basins, well we've still got one. The wash hand basin you had used to have a bowl in the old - go along - you had to have a tin - go alon
g
 to Ironpark Hall along there and where they had the old jug of soup and we used to have that and a - a slice of bread with it and bring it - see, bring it back home and put it - so that soup was - what we call now good soup but I mean then it was - a lux
ury. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 This was for lunchtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
This for dinner. Yes, dinner. Well I mean, not - not like going to the schools like they do have now, feed them, go along - see used to share a big bowl - a bit - we used to take a white - a big wash handbasin see. Bring it home and my -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 This would be sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 1900}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Before - before then I think, I daresay before then because I was sixteen in 1910. See I was going on so it must have been well before that, see. Before I left school. So you can tell what i
t was like. As I say, go along there and carry that jug. Get on the queue. Yes, still - I was still - I - I always tell all of them that was the good old days, they caught them, them old days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did you have anything different on certain days, on Sundays for example?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Well - yes, yes. I told you that cods head.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 What did you used to do on Sundays, have anything special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Church - we had to go to church. We had to go - all - all of us had to go to St. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 George\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  church in the morning, afternoon and night. And we had to take the numbers. Remember the numbers of those - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 hymns}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 that were sung to let them know we got there because they used to have a monthly magazine and in that monthly magazine were the numbers of the songs, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 hymns}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  that were s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 n
g. So if we didn't have tab on the numbers - oh - we had to go to church. And - and that's what I've never done to my children, make them go. Yet one of them's very religious.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did you eat anything different on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No. We would boil - bo
il a - boil a - we had cods head for dinner. And you can tell what much we got off that, just a little bit of jelly, little bit of fish. I - I - I've known the time when - they could afford a haddock and - when - as children like see and mother wouldn't h
ave any or dad'd have some, see it would be a small one but we would have the liquor that was - boiled in, soak our bread in. That was - that was a treat. And of course you had a taste of haddock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Do you know what you had for evening meals in those days, for tea?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
For tea - tea? Just bread and butter or bread and jam, margarine or something. Well - bread and butter it was. But it was generally bread and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did your mother or father bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Make their own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Bottle fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Make pickles wine or medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did they brew any beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. Oh my mother was dead against beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did your father and mother grow their own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
No. Well see of course - most of the time ever I know he was a - he was soldiering right up 'til just after the Boer War you see, well that finished in 1901. Well then - in 1901 and 02 he was at home for - well all the last was - well see to 1914, 
he died in 1915. See, so there wasn't no time, all he done was casual jobs then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 buy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 any fresh vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh - oh yes, 'course they like - I mean, me mother - had a little - earned a little bit see sometimes. I think - she wor
ked for people with money, that she'd know on this 'ere business sitting up with them and all that. Of course they always paid her a bit more and then we'd have a bit better stuff, see, she used to look after us. I mean, it's - I don't remember but - she 
u
sed to do it and my - my mother's sisters were well off. My - one - had a - a boss of the manufacturing of matches. Won't mention his name in case it gets out see, but - he was well off. Actually he's gone to America and all of that. Well this was - every
 Christmas they would wend us down like some toys or some sort, like he old Fish and Fuzz, Grandma and Ludo and all them sort of things. Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 
But otherwise all we'd have would - off of our own people we could have us an orange, think theirself lucky you 
see, then we used to get - I mean, you could twenty-four oranges then as you might say for shilling down the market place on a Saturday you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Like for a sixpence you'd have - dozen oranges, you'd have one of them in your stocking and a bit of coal and -
 this is from your auntie so and so, all the other stuff was. They was - at that - although they was - my - my - mother's - mother's sister-in-law like was - well ours - I mean ours what we - there was never - never showed it. Barring my mother's sister. 
My mother's sister would show it. In your place she would say. Even during the first world war I went up in the Army and the Army - I was at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 Chatham}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 , I've been at their place dozens of times, Woodford Green Essex they was. Fine big house, oh - all these people that play golf and all that. And - I sat down to - on a big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 lawn,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 I was dressed in the old uniform, with my cousin - the oldest cousin. And all - funny thing, I had a sister named Violet. Well, she's still alive now. And all of a sudden I heard from th
e window, Violet, you know they could talk posh, Violet - be careful. And I was old enough to know see, I was in the Army, I was twenty. Hit me like that, I thought - and hurt me. Put me down there on the floor. Don't get too sociable - old fashioned sort
 
of attitude. Yet they was - yet - the one who had the money, her - her father was - tops, he was. It's very funny how they went like that see - and the other one was always traveling about, the other one - my mother's other sister, I never see her, not at
 all. Yet they always seat us something Christmas. And all during the war - he sent me out - so many cigarettes, I used to smoke }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 every time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  I went there, they come every month. You can tell he had money 'cos he used to send them through bond. 'Course that was the Yorkshire mill what he owned. But it was terrible before 1910. It was horrible, it was horrible.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 You didn't have any livestock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh - forget now. Not many. Not many. It'd - it'd b
e always soup and what's say - bread and jam, bread and jam if you can talk about jam you could talk on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did you ever have tinned fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 There was no tinned stuff about much then, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Or tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Not tinned meat, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did you get extra meat such as rabbits from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
That - that's what my father kept - now, I told her - last week I had one, my father he kept rabbits. Only for a time at the back. But I remember that when I was young the poor old rabbi
t arched his back like this and - my father was a cruel man. He put that back in the hutch, he couldn't - couldn't kill it. Now what do you think of that. Had to get somebody else to do it, ill the rabbit. Then he got - after that he got rid of the lot, l
ike sold them for beer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 He sold them for beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Yes, afterwards yes. He used to keep them for - for eat, yes. Because he had hutch upon hutch that he built in his spare time. Somebody give him a rabbit or two and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 You didn't get any rabbits from poaching given to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh yes. Mother - she often had less food, she often had less food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Did your father have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Oh no, he was - he wasn't - he wasn't a - a ; a man like greedy and all that, I wouldn't say that about him - no. His had faults was drink - he - he would give; to other people more than he'd give home. I - when we lived up top that's going some now -
 in Reading the casual ward used to be like - that's the casual ward, that's where the out of works and - what do you call them - tramps. That's where the Battle Hospital is now, the country - the chest department there. They used to come there on the nig
h
t and they'd have to work in the morning. Barring - Saturday nights - Sunday mornings. They wouldn't have to work Sunday mornings. There was always more in there Saturday night, 'cos they never had to do so much work for their - for a night's sleep. They 
a
lways come along with the old tinkers and all that and - you can see the gates, not there now, there used to be a shop up there - at - I used to live next to that there - Priorities was up there, seven seventy it was. And a man'd come round the back and g
ot over the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 fence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
, came up to the back place like that and my father was having his breakfast and a knock come on the back door, he shouldn't have come that way at all but he come in through the gate, knocked on that door and I went to the door and I said, 
now we haven't got - we haven't - we was having some food at that time. My father took it out and give him what he had. Now beat it. Give the tramp his food. What do you think of that, and he went without himself. That's - you can't - you can't understand
 
a bloke like that. Good at that point you see. Give to them. And - and he was that - he was that sort of fashion like say, I've got to say he was a drunkard, because I see man after the war come back - was abroad but he died - he died on that but it was a
 hospital during the first world war. He said, George - - this is words he used. Did your old man like drink, he said. He says, do you know what he was doing in that hospital, do you know where I was before. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 He said, bring me some in a medicine bottle, smuggle it in, in a medicine bottle. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
In a medicine bottle he had it. Good heavens, yes, he was a bit of - but honestly he was - although I say it - I've got a daughter who's very religious see. I am an atheist by rights if I spoke me mind. I - I - I can't see 
as anybody that had anything to do like it. And I never sent my daughters to church - from - they can go if they like. First thing the next one went - on her own, went to Salvationist, went to Methodist and all over, never stopped her from going. I never 
s
aid you must go. Because we was made to go. See? And she took it on her own. She's a - she hit me hard once, she said, you remember dad, you never sent me to church? Oh I felt terrible. I felt terrible. But I - I never sent her because we was made to do t
h
is and made to do that, made to do the other. No fear. Knocked about. And I've never touched one of my girls with me finger. They're good - good girls too. They're better for it, in the old days they believed in the strap coming in, bashing you with it. H
e
 - he - he - I - I'll tell you another thing, all - he - we've waited outside, my eldest sister and meself and that, wait - been outside that bedroom door above this house here - waiting to dash out - what - he was going to kill my mother. I've seen my fa
t
her - over the copper, I'm not telling one word of a lie, with a razor in his hand and - drunk 1-drunk, and my poor mother had been out all night. He come across, so we - we was holding his hand. And he didn't know it because he didn't know what he was do
ing. He was killing the best woman in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12075973\charrsid9580092 the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
world. He didn't know he was doing it. In the old days the pubs opened from nine 'til - half past six like - from six o'clock in the morning 'til eleven o'clock at night it was terrible. Terrible. Fights and all tha
t. I mean, it was the children that suffered in the end. Children - we never had it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No, no, no, silence, no. You mustn't criticize anything either. No, nor answer back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Could you choose what you wanted to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Oh no. You was lucky - you was lucky to have something on the table to eat, I - I mean, there was fortunate people admitted. Some of them was all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 What was your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1399755\charrsid9580092 parent\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092  attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Left some? Do you think they let - they'd leave - there was nothing to leave. I - I said that when I told you. They just said the bread was dry and upstairs I went to bed with a good hiding to none. Didn't have any. Never had any food at all. No fear.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Oh yes. Oh yes, yes, yes. Or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 You wouldn't have to wait until it was offered?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. One thing that you was brought - we was brought
 up with - father - good manners. Oh - that's what I tell you about the boots. And hands in your pockets. He wouldn't have none of that. Try to be respectable if you wasn't. I mean if you never had it you got - could make yourself poorer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
Yes, I suppose - if there was some - if you - if there was a bit you could have it perhaps. Ninety-nine times out of a hundred there wasn't any there you - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 And sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Yes, yes, you had to sit still and - don't talk either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 No. No. And we had to say grace. We had to say grace. That's what I - I think
 it's a farce. But you we had to do it, say grace before - had to say our prayers at night. To mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4540718 GR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 When they said yes, when mother and father said you when they were finished, when you - when you were all fini
shed then you - like that you see. You could ask to leave and - they might let you leave but - you mustn't do it - wouldn't dare do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745245 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 You ask sat at the table for a meal did you?
