tairs this - Mrs Harrison her name was, she laid - laid on the bed with my mother and hugged her to her, my mother was always tender hearted like that. And heard her cry, nursie, nursie, she said, get well, get well. Well I - I - I - I remember it, I thou
g
ht what a splendid loving woman she was. And how nice my mother must have been. You could ask her I mean - I get there on hundreds of thousands of babies like that she did get rid of you know. And you remember - do you remember Brews who had a tobacconist
 along the Oxford Road? They - they're at Cavershan now, brew, they had a big shop where the - where }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9308085\charrsid9580092 Sargeants}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 is now, that gig shop. You know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9308085\charrsid9580092 Sargeants,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5376311\charrsid9580092 
 the cutlers along the Oxford Road, Oxford Street. Well - my father died in November - of 1915, I was ou
